{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Uam6C9EdBdty3DPMyK37vk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Implementation Checklist\n     2→- [ ] 1. Confirm all spec and repository constraints for Spec 05-gha-agent against `.ralph/specs/05-gha-agent.md`, `.ralph/task.md`, and shared agent patterns.\n     3→- [ ] 2. Create `skills/gha-agent/scripts/gha-agent.sh` with `#!/usr/bin/env bash`, `set -euo pipefail`, shared-lib source, and FR-1 universal contract.\n     4→- [ ] 3. Implement `RUN_LINT` and `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST`/`TMPDIR_ROOT`/`CHANGED_FILES` integration through shared helpers.\n     5→- [ ] 4. Implement `usage()` and CLI contract: no-arg default `all`, explicit `lint`, `help`/`-h`/`--help`, `--fail-fast`, and unknown-command handling.\n     6→- [ ] 5. Implement required-tool validation with `need actionlint` and `--help` behavior that does not require project context or tool availability.\n     7→- [ ] 6. Implement `run_lint` with `.github/workflows` discovery, CHANGED_FILES scoping, skip-paths, actionlint execution, log capture, and mandated fix hint.\n     8→- [ ] 7. Add explicit `all` orchestration using `should_continue` and step toggles.\n     9→- [ ] 8. Add `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger keywords and minimal allowed-tool patterns for `RUN_*`, `CHANGED_FILES`, and `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST`/`TMPDIR_ROOT`.\n    10→- [ ] 9. Add `tests/gha-agent/clean/` fixtures (`scenario.env`, `.github/workflows/ci.yml`) with `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"actionlint\"` and `RUN_ARGS=\"all\"`.\n    11→- [ ] 10. Add `tests/gha-agent/issues/` fixtures (`scenario.env`, `.github/workflows/bad.yml`) with an actionlint-detectable failure and `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"actionlint\"`.\n    12→- [ ] 11. Extend `install.sh` to include `gha-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency check section, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet.\n    13→- [ ] 12. Extend `README.md` with `gha-agent` in Available Agents and usage examples.\n    14→- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema.\n    15→- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n    16→\n    17→## Architecture Review\n    18→\n    19→### Overall system design and component boundaries\n    20→`gha-agent` is a single-step domain wrapper around the existing shared runtime and orchestration conventions. The architecture is unchanged relative to existing agents.\n    21→\n    22→- Script layer: `skills/gha-agent/scripts/gha-agent.sh` handles argument parsing, discovery, scoped command execution, and result rendering.\n    23→- Shared runtime: `lib/x-agent-common.sh` supplies common setup, locking, output formatting helpers, fail-fast semantics, and dependency checks.\n    24→- Registration layer: `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md`, `install.sh`, and `README.md` register the agent and document usage.\n    25→- Validation layer: `tests/gha-agent/*` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh` validate fixture behavior and shell compliance.\n    26→\n    27→Dependency flow is linear: plan/scope/validate -> discovery -> command execution -> output/logging -> aggregated overall result.\n    28→\n    29→### Dependency graph and coupling concerns\n    30→`gha-agent` depends on:\n    31→- local path conventions via `SCRIPT_DIR/../../../lib`\n    32→- `actionlint` binary availability in PATH\n    33→- test fixtures under `.github/workflows`\n    34→\n    35→`tests/run-scenarios.sh` depends on exact script path and executable bit. `install.sh` depends on the same paths for distribution and discovery.\n    36→\n    37→Coupling risks:\n    38→- Path coupling: wrong `LIB_DIR` resolution breaks all shared helpers.\n    39→- Install coupling: missing `gha-agent` in `SKILLS` makes agent undiscoverable.\n    40→- Tool coupling: absence of `actionlint` should gracefully skip via fixture tool requirements, not script crash.\n    41→\n    42→### Data flow patterns and potential bottlenecks\n    43→Data flow per invocation:\n    44→1. Parse flags/command and help path.\n    45→2. `need actionlint` then shared `setup_outdir` + `setup_lock`.\n    46→3. Resolve workspace scope from `CHANGED_FILES` or `.github/workflows` discovery.\n    47→4. Run actionlint command.\n    48→5. Write full output to `$OUTDIR/lint.log` and emit trimmed diagnostics.\n    49→6. Print final overall pass/fail and return exit code.\n    50→\n    51→Bottlenecks are minimal and limited to filesystem walks for workflow file discovery and `actionlint` execution over YAML files.\n    52→\n    53→### Scaling characteristics and single points of failure\n    54→- Scales linearly with number of workflow files and size of workflow YAML.\n    55→- Single-point-of-failure remains the lockfile and temp log lifecycle per agent name; if lock cannot be acquired because of stale FD or FS issue, runs serialize or proceed (depending on system behavior).\n    56→- In lockless environments, overlapping runs can contend for shared `.github/workflows` read operations but these are read-only; output interleaving risk is avoided by per-run log dir.\n    57→\n    58→### Security architecture\n    59→- No external network/API interactions are introduced.\n    60→- Inputs are local paths/environment variables and should be treated as trusted because agents are run inside a local repo.\n    61→- Defensive controls:\n    62→  - command execution only through fixed executable `actionlint` with validated path arguments.\n    63→  - quoting of discovered file paths in argument arrays to reduce glob/word-splitting effects.\n    64→  - shared lock prevents concurrent overlapping runs from clobbering workspace assumptions.\n    65→\n    66→### Key architectural options and tradeoffs\n    67→Decision A: CHANGED_FILES behavior\n    68→- Option 1: Ignore `CHANGED_FILES`; always run `actionlint` on all workflow files.\n    69→  - Effort: lowest, simplest.\n    70→  - Risk: slower and violates FR-3/scoped behavior.\n    71→  - Future impact: weakens incremental behavior as specs scale.\n    72→- Option 2: Filter CHANGED_FILES to workflow paths and pass scoped list; fall back to all when empty.\n    73→  - Effort: low.\n    74→  - Risk: scoped file expansion edge cases with spaces/unusual filenames.\n    75→  - Future impact: matches broader repo style and gives strong incremental behavior.\n    76→- Option 3: Implement a generic scope abstraction for all agents in shared lib.\n    77→  - Effort: high.\n    78→  - Risk: migration ripple to non-GitHub agents.\n    79→  - Future impact: possible reuse but out-of-scope for single spec.\n    80→\n    81→Chosen: Option 2. It satisfies FR-3 and keeps future scalability while avoiding cross-spec churn.\n    82→\n    83→Decision B: Scope discovery strategy\n    84→- Option 1: `find .github/workflows -type f` and filter extensions.\n    85→  - Effort: low.\n    86→  - Risk: extra scan if repo has many nested workflow-like paths.\n    87→  - Impact: predictable and easy to test.\n    88→- Option 2: Use `git ls-files \".github/workflows\"` only.\n    89→  - Effort: low.\n    90→  - Risk: misses untracked workflow additions.\n    91→  - Impact: weak for dirty working directories.\n    92→\n    93→Chosen: Option 1 (filesystem-first) for correctness in all working-tree states.\n    94→\n    95→Decision C: Skip semantics when no workflows exist\n    96→- Option 1: Return FAIL with explicit instruction.\n    97→  - Impact: alerts caller but may be noisy in repos without workflows.\n    98→- Option 2: Return SKIP with explicit reason.\n    99→  - Impact: aligns FR-4 and consistent with other agents.\n   100→\n   101→Chosen: Option 2.\n   102→\n   103→Implications for future specs: keep this same skip-first pattern in new single-scope agents (helm/docker/kube/etc.) when discovery paths are optional.\n   104→\n   105→## Code Quality Planning\n   106→\n   107→### Code organization and module structure\n   108→Keep `gha-agent` domain file under ~200 lines by relying on shared helpers for:\n   109→- cleanup and locking\n   110→- step timing\n   111→- result formatting\n   112→- lock acquisition\n   113→\n   114→`gha-agent.sh` should therefore contain only:\n   115→- header + shared-lib source\n   116→- usage/help text\n   117→- scope resolver\n   118→- one command function (`run_lint`)\n   119→- command dispatcher (`main`)\n   120→\n   121→### DRY opportunities and repetition plan\n   122→Use shared `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `step`, and `fmt_elapsed`; avoid duplicating trap/lock code. The only domain-specific duplication may be argument normalization for actionlint command modes.\n   123→\n   124→### Error handling patterns for explicit edge cases\n   125→All edge cases must map to deterministic output and exit semantics:\n   126→- missing required argument context for help should not fail on `need()`\n   127→- missing `actionlint` should fail with code 2 via `need`\n   128→- no `.github/workflows` directory should produce `Result: SKIP (no .github/workflows/ directory found)`\n   129→- CHANGED_FILES set but no matching workflow paths should produce `Result: SKIP` (clear reason)\n   130→- actionlint failures should produce `Result: FAIL` and `Fix:` hint\n   131→- successful run should clean temp logs unless `KEEP_DIR=1`\n   132→- keep `overall_ok` and `--fail-fast` behavior consistent in command path\n   133→\n   134→### Technical debt prevention\n   135→- Keep path filtering logic centralized in one helper function and reused by `run_lint`.\n   136→- Keep fix hint text standardized and deterministic.\n   137→- Keep failure output length bounded by `MAX_LINES`.\n   138→- Do not add per-agent custom trap logic that bypasses shared lib.\n   139→- Keep CHANGED_FILES parsing consistent with existing agents (space-delimited list assumption) to avoid creating new divergence.\n   140→\n   141→### Engineering level\n   142→Use `engineered enough` behavior:\n   143→- no over-abstracted generic YAML parser\n   144→- explicit checks for expected files\n   145→- straightforward bash arrays for scoped files\n   146→- avoid brittle command substitutions with unguarded glob expansion.\n   147→\n   148→## Test Strategy\n   149→\n   150→### Coverage model\n   151→- Unit/isolated behavior is command-level in shell execution terms (scope resolution and conditional branch behavior).\n   152→- Integration behavior is `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent` with clean and issues fixtures.\n   153→- End-to-end validation includes running full repository checks through `ralph validate work`.\n   154→\n   155→### Critical edge-case coverage\n   156→- clean workflow: valid `ci.yml` passes with `EXPECT_EXIT=0`\n   157→- issues workflow: invalid workflow fails with `EXPECT_EXIT=1`\n   158→- missing workflow directory: runs should SKIP and return PASS\n   159→- CHANGED_FILES scoped to non-workflow files: should SKIP if no workflow matches\n   160→- CHANGED_FILES scoped to one workflow file: should only lint that file\n   161→- all mode on skip case: default still follows output contract\n   162→- `--fail-fast` with an explicit failing lint: no extra steps exist, but guard still exercised and should not regress\n   163→- install/README presence checks via review against touched files.\n   164→\n   165→### Failure modes and error paths\n   166→- absent `actionlint` in environment\n   167→- corrupted workflow YAML causing actionlint parser errors\n   168→- scenario wrapper passing spaces in workflow filenames (documented limitation)\n   169→- help invocation with nonexistent project root/toolchain\n   170→- missing `.github/workflows` directory\n   171→\n   172→### Assertion strength expectations\n   173→- assert exact exit codes through `EXPECT_EXIT`\n   174→- assert `Result:` lines include PASS/FAIL/SKIP states\n   175→- assert `Fix:` exists on FAIL\n   176→- assert logs are produced under `$OUTDIR` and `Overall` summary appears\n   177→- assert skip-path messages are explicit and actionable.\n   178→\n   179→## Performance Considerations\n   180→\n   181→- No database usage.\n   182→- Avoid repeated file-system scans by resolving scope once before running any checks.\n   183→- `find .github/workflows` is O(n) in repository size; in monorepos this is bounded and one pass.\n   184→- `actionlint` runtime is the dominant cost; CHANGED_FILES reduces this in incremental scenarios.\n   185→- Logging to disk is O(output size) and safer than memory buffering.\n   186→- No caching required for first implementation; cacheable future optimization: optionally store last-scan path list per run path if repeated invocations become hot.\n   187→\n   188→## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n   189→\n   190→1. What: confirm implementation requirements and concrete integration points.\n   191→Why: ensures implementation is aligned with the backlog, FR list, and existing conventions before edits.\n   192→How: read spec, `docs/agents/*`, `lib/x-agent-common.sh`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh`, and install/readme patterns in a single pass.\n   193→Edge cases: skip discovery of any missing existing assumptions (shared helpers, lock path, scenario contract).\n   194→Tests: no code tests; this is planning verification.\n   195→Risks: stale plan if a dependency from existing scripts is missed.\n   196→\n   197→2. What: create `skills/gha-agent/scripts/` and `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md` directories and scaffolding.\n   198→Why: filesystem path parity with existing agents is required for installer and discovery.\n   199→How: mkdir new directories and align file naming exactly with `<name>-agent` conventions.\n   200→Edge cases: ensure executable bit for script path in script and installer contexts.\n   201→Tests: `bash -n` not yet required but script should eventually satisfy shell syntax checks.\n   202→Risks: missing directories break install and scenario path resolution.\n   203→\n   204→3. What: build the script header and shared-lib integration.\n   205→Why: FR-1 mandates sourcing the shared library and keeps logic below 200 lines.\n   206→How: add `set -euo pipefail`, comments with required/deps, compute `SCRIPT_DIR`/`LIB_DIR`, and source `x-agent-common.sh`.\n   207→Edge cases: keep source path `../../../lib` exactly; avoid side effects on source.\n   208→Tests: run script help once after implementation to confirm no early side effects.\n   209→Risks: wrong relative path to lib causes runtime failure.\n   210→\n   211→4. What: define knobs and universal env defaults.\n   212→Why: ensures universal knob support and per-step control.\n   213→How: set `RUN_LINT=1` and rely on shared vars from common lib for all universal knobs.\n   214→Edge cases: ensure no local override shadows shared defaults for `CHANGED_FILES` and line control.\n   215→Tests: scenario run with `RUN_LINT=0` should skip step path if using `all`.\n   216→Risks: incorrect toggle evaluation causing lint run when disabled.\n   217→\n   218→5. What: implement help and argument parser.\n   219→Why: FR-5 requires `--help`/`help`/`-h`, and usage should work regardless of project context.\n   220→How: handle help and `--fail-fast` before `need actionlint`; dispatch commands `lint`, `all`, and default `all`.\n   221→Edge cases: unknown command should print usage and exit 2.\n   222→Tests: `./gha-agent.sh help`, `-h`, `--help` in empty directory.\n   223→Risks: accidental `need` before help causing false failures.\n   224→\n   225→6. What: implement workflow discovery and CHANGED_FILES scoping.\n   226→Why: FR-7 requires scoped behavior and skip behavior when no target exists.\n   227→How: resolver returns targets from changed files only when `CHANGED_FILES` is non-empty and matching `*.yml` or `*.yaml` under `.github/workflows/`; otherwise discover all workflow files from that directory.\n   228→Edge cases: `CHANGED_FILES` includes non-workflow entries, duplicates, or missing files.\n   229→Tests: run with scoped and non-scoped environment values in fixture and local checks.\n   230→Risks: path spaces and shell splitting mismatch (repo-wide convention already uses space-delimited values).\n   231→\n   232→7. What: implement `run_lint` as the single step.\n   233→Why: meets FR-6 and FR-4 by executing actionlint with structured reporting.\n   234→How: print step, handle empty workflow targets (`SKIP`), execute `actionlint` with targets, capture stdout+stderr to `$OUTDIR/lint.log`, report failures with truncated context and `Fix: resolve the workflow errors above, then re-run: /gha-agent lint`.\n   235→Edge cases: actionlint output includes both stdout/stderr; use redirection accordingly.\n   236→Tests: issues fixture should fail and include actionable error context in output.\n   237→Risks: forgetting non-zero return handling and marking pass incorrectly.\n   238→\n   239→8. What: implement `main` flow with all command semantics.\n   240→Why: ensures FR-4 output contract, FR-5 fail-fast behavior, and stable exit codes.\n   241→How: initialize `overall_ok=1`, setup outdir+lock after tool checks and parse, run `run_lint` when command is `lint`/`all` with `RUN_LINT`/`should_continue`, emit final result via `print_overall`.\n   242→Edge cases: `--fail-fast=1` does not regress in single-step mode but still must be parsed and respected.\n   243→Tests: fixture expectations for default all and explicit command.\n   244→Risks: omitting `set -e` interactions around explicit return handling and final aggregate status.\n   245→\n   246→9. What: add SKILL.md registration docs.\n   247→Why: required by FR-11 and for agent discoverability.\n   248→How: mirror existing style with concise trigger language for actionlint workflows and allowed-tools for run command plus env overrides (`RUN_LINT`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `MAX_LINES`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`).\n   249→Edge cases: include command forms (`lint`, `all`).\n   250→Tests: manual inspection only; validate policy compatibility by review.\n   251→Risks: omitted allowed-tools pattern breaks tool-call execution.\n   252→\n   253→10. What: add scenario fixtures.\n   254→Why: required by FR-12 and FR-13.\n   255→How: add `tests/gha-agent/clean/scenario.env` and issue fixture with minimal valid/invalid workflow files under `.github/workflows`.\n   256→Edge cases: make issue file deterministic (invalid runs-on/type, expression syntax, etc.) and avoid ambiguous YAML warnings.\n   257→Tests: run scenario label checks via `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent`.\n   258→Risks: too-brittle fixture depending on specific actionlint version/version-specific warnings.\n   259→\n   260→11. What: update distribution docs.\n   261→Why: FR-13 requires installer and docs updates to make agent visible and installable.\n   262→How: modify `install.sh` `SKILLS`, dependency hints, and AGENTS snippet for gha-agent; update README available-agent row and quick usage section.\n   263→Edge cases: keep existing installation order and interactive prompts intact.\n   264→Tests: validate installer help snippet includes gha-agent line and `run all` discoverability not harmed.\n   265→Risks: accidental format regression in install dependency checks.\n   266→\n   267→12. What: run validation and complete sign-off.\n   268→Why: confirm acceptance criteria and catch integration/regression issues before WORK phase.\n   269→How: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent`, shellcheck on new script+SKILL and relevant files via `tests/run-scenarios.sh shellcheck`, then `ralph validate work`.\n   270→Edge cases: fixture/tool mismatch should be explicit skips vs fails.\n   271→Tests: full plan-phase checks.\n   272→Risks: validation toolchain dependency (shellcheck missing) causing false failure.\n   273→\n   274→13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n   275→14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n   276→\n   277→## Decision Log\n   278→\n   279→- Decision 1: Use per-spec shared-lib source pattern instead of local utility duplication.\n   280→  - Options considered: keep duplicated bootstrap code in new script, or source `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\n   281→  - Chosen: source shared lib.\n   282→  - Why: consistent with backlog scope and line budget.\n   283→  - Impact: lower maintenance, same patterns as existing agents, uniform fail-safe semantics.\n   284→\n   285→- Decision 2: Implement strict skip-first behavior for missing `.github/workflows`.\n   286→  - Options considered: return FAIL, return SKIP, auto-create dir.\n   287→  - Chosen: `SKIP` with explicit reason.\n   288→  - Why: aligns FR-4 requirement text and avoids false failures in non-GHA repos.\n   289→  - Impact: predictable behavior for repos with only Terraform/Python etc.\n   290→\n   291→- Decision 3: Preserve local command semantics for `all` with one-step body.\n   292→  - Options considered: special-case `all` with no step expansion vs route through `lint`.\n   293→  - Chosen: route `all` through step dispatch to keep consistent `overall_ok` and fail-fast handling.\n   294→  - Why: future-proofing for additional steps.\n   295→  - Impact: minimal complexity and consistent UX across agents.\n   296→\n   297→## Edge Cases and Risks\n   298→\n   299→- `.github/workflows` directory does not exist in repo.\n   300→- CHANGED_FILES set but no workflow path matches and no direct discovery files exist.\n   301→- CHANGED_FILES contains non-workflow files only.\n   302→- CHANGED_FILES path separators differ on platform (existing convention keeps space-delimited paths only).\n   303→- `actionlint` unavailable even though fixture says required tool present.\n   304→- actionlint emits non-zero while no output, or output without diagnostics.\n   305→- Help invoked before toolchain install or from non-repo directory.\n   306→- CI versus local behavior around log line truncation due shared MAX_LINES defaults.\n   307→- Installer path mismatch on remote install if `gha-agent` files absent or script not executable.\n   308→- README/AGENTS snippets can become stale if not updated with new agent line.\n   309→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04f1945e-7bf3-4940-ab64-46803dcd06b1","uuid":"ab7c7886-7961-4881-ac72-3bdd047cf7d6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/work-plan.txt","content":"## Implementation Checklist\n- [ ] 1. Confirm all spec and repository constraints for Spec 05-gha-agent against `.ralph/specs/05-gha-agent.md`, `.ralph/task.md`, and shared agent patterns.\n- [ ] 2. Create `skills/gha-agent/scripts/gha-agent.sh` with `#!/usr/bin/env bash`, `set -euo pipefail`, shared-lib source, and FR-1 universal contract.\n- [ ] 3. Implement `RUN_LINT` and `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST`/`TMPDIR_ROOT`/`CHANGED_FILES` integration through shared helpers.\n- [ ] 4. Implement `usage()` and CLI contract: no-arg default `all`, explicit `lint`, `help`/`-h`/`--help`, `--fail-fast`, and unknown-command handling.\n- [ ] 5. Implement required-tool validation with `need actionlint` and `--help` behavior that does not require project context or tool availability.\n- [ ] 6. Implement `run_lint` with `.github/workflows` discovery, CHANGED_FILES scoping, skip-paths, actionlint execution, log capture, and mandated fix hint.\n- [ ] 7. Add explicit `all` orchestration using `should_continue` and step toggles.\n- [ ] 8. Add `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger keywords and minimal allowed-tool patterns for `RUN_*`, `CHANGED_FILES`, and `MAX_LINES`/`KEEP_DIR`/`FAIL_FAST`/`TMPDIR_ROOT`.\n- [ ] 9. Add `tests/gha-agent/clean/` fixtures (`scenario.env`, `.github/workflows/ci.yml`) with `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"actionlint\"` and `RUN_ARGS=\"all\"`.\n- [ ] 10. Add `tests/gha-agent/issues/` fixtures (`scenario.env`, `.github/workflows/bad.yml`) with an actionlint-detectable failure and `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"actionlint\"`.\n- [ ] 11. Extend `install.sh` to include `gha-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency check section, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet.\n- [ ] 12. Extend `README.md` with `gha-agent` in Available Agents and usage examples.\n- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema.\n- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n\n## Architecture Review\n\n### Overall system design and component boundaries\n`gha-agent` is a single-step domain wrapper around the existing shared runtime and orchestration conventions. The architecture is unchanged relative to existing agents.\n\n- Script layer: `skills/gha-agent/scripts/gha-agent.sh` handles argument parsing, discovery, scoped command execution, and result rendering.\n- Shared runtime: `lib/x-agent-common.sh` supplies common setup, locking, output formatting helpers, fail-fast semantics, and dependency checks.\n- Registration layer: `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md`, `install.sh`, and `README.md` register the agent and document usage.\n- Validation layer: `tests/gha-agent/*` and `tests/run-scenarios.sh` validate fixture behavior and shell compliance.\n\nDependency flow is linear: plan/scope/validate -> discovery -> command execution -> output/logging -> aggregated overall result.\n\n### Dependency graph and coupling concerns\n`gha-agent` depends on:\n- local path conventions via `SCRIPT_DIR/../../../lib`\n- `actionlint` binary availability in PATH\n- test fixtures under `.github/workflows`\n\n`tests/run-scenarios.sh` depends on exact script path and executable bit. `install.sh` depends on the same paths for distribution and discovery.\n\nCoupling risks:\n- Path coupling: wrong `LIB_DIR` resolution breaks all shared helpers.\n- Install coupling: missing `gha-agent` in `SKILLS` makes agent undiscoverable.\n- Tool coupling: absence of `actionlint` should gracefully skip via fixture tool requirements, not script crash.\n\n### Data flow patterns and potential bottlenecks\nData flow per invocation:\n1. Parse flags/command and help path.\n2. `need actionlint` then shared `setup_outdir` + `setup_lock`.\n3. Resolve workspace scope from `CHANGED_FILES` or `.github/workflows` discovery.\n4. Run actionlint command.\n5. Write full output to `$OUTDIR/lint.log` and emit trimmed diagnostics.\n6. Print final overall pass/fail and return exit code.\n\nBottlenecks are minimal and limited to filesystem walks for workflow file discovery and `actionlint` execution over YAML files.\n\n### Scaling characteristics and single points of failure\n- Scales linearly with number of workflow files and size of workflow YAML.\n- Single-point-of-failure remains the lockfile and temp log lifecycle per agent name; if lock cannot be acquired because of stale FD or FS issue, runs serialize or proceed (depending on system behavior).\n- In lockless environments, overlapping runs can contend for shared `.github/workflows` read operations but these are read-only; output interleaving risk is avoided by per-run log dir.\n\n### Security architecture\n- No external network/API interactions are introduced.\n- Inputs are local paths/environment variables and should be treated as trusted because agents are run inside a local repo.\n- Defensive controls:\n  - command execution only through fixed executable `actionlint` with validated path arguments.\n  - quoting of discovered file paths in argument arrays to reduce glob/word-splitting effects.\n  - shared lock prevents concurrent overlapping runs from clobbering workspace assumptions.\n\n### Key architectural options and tradeoffs\nDecision A: CHANGED_FILES behavior\n- Option 1: Ignore `CHANGED_FILES`; always run `actionlint` on all workflow files.\n  - Effort: lowest, simplest.\n  - Risk: slower and violates FR-3/scoped behavior.\n  - Future impact: weakens incremental behavior as specs scale.\n- Option 2: Filter CHANGED_FILES to workflow paths and pass scoped list; fall back to all when empty.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: scoped file expansion edge cases with spaces/unusual filenames.\n  - Future impact: matches broader repo style and gives strong incremental behavior.\n- Option 3: Implement a generic scope abstraction for all agents in shared lib.\n  - Effort: high.\n  - Risk: migration ripple to non-GitHub agents.\n  - Future impact: possible reuse but out-of-scope for single spec.\n\nChosen: Option 2. It satisfies FR-3 and keeps future scalability while avoiding cross-spec churn.\n\nDecision B: Scope discovery strategy\n- Option 1: `find .github/workflows -type f` and filter extensions.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: extra scan if repo has many nested workflow-like paths.\n  - Impact: predictable and easy to test.\n- Option 2: Use `git ls-files \".github/workflows\"` only.\n  - Effort: low.\n  - Risk: misses untracked workflow additions.\n  - Impact: weak for dirty working directories.\n\nChosen: Option 1 (filesystem-first) for correctness in all working-tree states.\n\nDecision C: Skip semantics when no workflows exist\n- Option 1: Return FAIL with explicit instruction.\n  - Impact: alerts caller but may be noisy in repos without workflows.\n- Option 2: Return SKIP with explicit reason.\n  - Impact: aligns FR-4 and consistent with other agents.\n\nChosen: Option 2.\n\nImplications for future specs: keep this same skip-first pattern in new single-scope agents (helm/docker/kube/etc.) when discovery paths are optional.\n\n## Code Quality Planning\n\n### Code organization and module structure\nKeep `gha-agent` domain file under ~200 lines by relying on shared helpers for:\n- cleanup and locking\n- step timing\n- result formatting\n- lock acquisition\n\n`gha-agent.sh` should therefore contain only:\n- header + shared-lib source\n- usage/help text\n- scope resolver\n- one command function (`run_lint`)\n- command dispatcher (`main`)\n\n### DRY opportunities and repetition plan\nUse shared `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `step`, and `fmt_elapsed`; avoid duplicating trap/lock code. The only domain-specific duplication may be argument normalization for actionlint command modes.\n\n### Error handling patterns for explicit edge cases\nAll edge cases must map to deterministic output and exit semantics:\n- missing required argument context for help should not fail on `need()`\n- missing `actionlint` should fail with code 2 via `need`\n- no `.github/workflows` directory should produce `Result: SKIP (no .github/workflows/ directory found)`\n- CHANGED_FILES set but no matching workflow paths should produce `Result: SKIP` (clear reason)\n- actionlint failures should produce `Result: FAIL` and `Fix:` hint\n- successful run should clean temp logs unless `KEEP_DIR=1`\n- keep `overall_ok` and `--fail-fast` behavior consistent in command path\n\n### Technical debt prevention\n- Keep path filtering logic centralized in one helper function and reused by `run_lint`.\n- Keep fix hint text standardized and deterministic.\n- Keep failure output length bounded by `MAX_LINES`.\n- Do not add per-agent custom trap logic that bypasses shared lib.\n- Keep CHANGED_FILES parsing consistent with existing agents (space-delimited list assumption) to avoid creating new divergence.\n\n### Engineering level\nUse `engineered enough` behavior:\n- no over-abstracted generic YAML parser\n- explicit checks for expected files\n- straightforward bash arrays for scoped files\n- avoid brittle command substitutions with unguarded glob expansion.\n\n## Test Strategy\n\n### Coverage model\n- Unit/isolated behavior is command-level in shell execution terms (scope resolution and conditional branch behavior).\n- Integration behavior is `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent` with clean and issues fixtures.\n- End-to-end validation includes running full repository checks through `ralph validate work`.\n\n### Critical edge-case coverage\n- clean workflow: valid `ci.yml` passes with `EXPECT_EXIT=0`\n- issues workflow: invalid workflow fails with `EXPECT_EXIT=1`\n- missing workflow directory: runs should SKIP and return PASS\n- CHANGED_FILES scoped to non-workflow files: should SKIP if no workflow matches\n- CHANGED_FILES scoped to one workflow file: should only lint that file\n- all mode on skip case: default still follows output contract\n- `--fail-fast` with an explicit failing lint: no extra steps exist, but guard still exercised and should not regress\n- install/README presence checks via review against touched files.\n\n### Failure modes and error paths\n- absent `actionlint` in environment\n- corrupted workflow YAML causing actionlint parser errors\n- scenario wrapper passing spaces in workflow filenames (documented limitation)\n- help invocation with nonexistent project root/toolchain\n- missing `.github/workflows` directory\n\n### Assertion strength expectations\n- assert exact exit codes through `EXPECT_EXIT`\n- assert `Result:` lines include PASS/FAIL/SKIP states\n- assert `Fix:` exists on FAIL\n- assert logs are produced under `$OUTDIR` and `Overall` summary appears\n- assert skip-path messages are explicit and actionable.\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n- No database usage.\n- Avoid repeated file-system scans by resolving scope once before running any checks.\n- `find .github/workflows` is O(n) in repository size; in monorepos this is bounded and one pass.\n- `actionlint` runtime is the dominant cost; CHANGED_FILES reduces this in incremental scenarios.\n- Logging to disk is O(output size) and safer than memory buffering.\n- No caching required for first implementation; cacheable future optimization: optionally store last-scan path list per run path if repeated invocations become hot.\n\n## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n\n1. What: confirm implementation requirements and concrete integration points.\nWhy: ensures implementation is aligned with the backlog, FR list, and existing conventions before edits.\nHow: read spec, `docs/agents/*`, `lib/x-agent-common.sh`, `tests/run-scenarios.sh`, and install/readme patterns in a single pass.\nEdge cases: skip discovery of any missing existing assumptions (shared helpers, lock path, scenario contract).\nTests: no code tests; this is planning verification.\nRisks: stale plan if a dependency from existing scripts is missed.\n\n2. What: create `skills/gha-agent/scripts/` and `skills/gha-agent/SKILL.md` directories and scaffolding.\nWhy: filesystem path parity with existing agents is required for installer and discovery.\nHow: mkdir new directories and align file naming exactly with `<name>-agent` conventions.\nEdge cases: ensure executable bit for script path in script and installer contexts.\nTests: `bash -n` not yet required but script should eventually satisfy shell syntax checks.\nRisks: missing directories break install and scenario path resolution.\n\n3. What: build the script header and shared-lib integration.\nWhy: FR-1 mandates sourcing the shared library and keeps logic below 200 lines.\nHow: add `set -euo pipefail`, comments with required/deps, compute `SCRIPT_DIR`/`LIB_DIR`, and source `x-agent-common.sh`.\nEdge cases: keep source path `../../../lib` exactly; avoid side effects on source.\nTests: run script help once after implementation to confirm no early side effects.\nRisks: wrong relative path to lib causes runtime failure.\n\n4. What: define knobs and universal env defaults.\nWhy: ensures universal knob support and per-step control.\nHow: set `RUN_LINT=1` and rely on shared vars from common lib for all universal knobs.\nEdge cases: ensure no local override shadows shared defaults for `CHANGED_FILES` and line control.\nTests: scenario run with `RUN_LINT=0` should skip step path if using `all`.\nRisks: incorrect toggle evaluation causing lint run when disabled.\n\n5. What: implement help and argument parser.\nWhy: FR-5 requires `--help`/`help`/`-h`, and usage should work regardless of project context.\nHow: handle help and `--fail-fast` before `need actionlint`; dispatch commands `lint`, `all`, and default `all`.\nEdge cases: unknown command should print usage and exit 2.\nTests: `./gha-agent.sh help`, `-h`, `--help` in empty directory.\nRisks: accidental `need` before help causing false failures.\n\n6. What: implement workflow discovery and CHANGED_FILES scoping.\nWhy: FR-7 requires scoped behavior and skip behavior when no target exists.\nHow: resolver returns targets from changed files only when `CHANGED_FILES` is non-empty and matching `*.yml` or `*.yaml` under `.github/workflows/`; otherwise discover all workflow files from that directory.\nEdge cases: `CHANGED_FILES` includes non-workflow entries, duplicates, or missing files.\nTests: run with scoped and non-scoped environment values in fixture and local checks.\nRisks: path spaces and shell splitting mismatch (repo-wide convention already uses space-delimited values).\n\n7. What: implement `run_lint` as the single step.\nWhy: meets FR-6 and FR-4 by executing actionlint with structured reporting.\nHow: print step, handle empty workflow targets (`SKIP`), execute `actionlint` with targets, capture stdout+stderr to `$OUTDIR/lint.log`, report failures with truncated context and `Fix: resolve the workflow errors above, then re-run: /gha-agent lint`.\nEdge cases: actionlint output includes both stdout/stderr; use redirection accordingly.\nTests: issues fixture should fail and include actionable error context in output.\nRisks: forgetting non-zero return handling and marking pass incorrectly.\n\n8. What: implement `main` flow with all command semantics.\nWhy: ensures FR-4 output contract, FR-5 fail-fast behavior, and stable exit codes.\nHow: initialize `overall_ok=1`, setup outdir+lock after tool checks and parse, run `run_lint` when command is `lint`/`all` with `RUN_LINT`/`should_continue`, emit final result via `print_overall`.\nEdge cases: `--fail-fast=1` does not regress in single-step mode but still must be parsed and respected.\nTests: fixture expectations for default all and explicit command.\nRisks: omitting `set -e` interactions around explicit return handling and final aggregate status.\n\n9. What: add SKILL.md registration docs.\nWhy: required by FR-11 and for agent discoverability.\nHow: mirror existing style with concise trigger language for actionlint workflows and allowed-tools for run command plus env overrides (`RUN_LINT`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `MAX_LINES`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`).\nEdge cases: include command forms (`lint`, `all`).\nTests: manual inspection only; validate policy compatibility by review.\nRisks: omitted allowed-tools pattern breaks tool-call execution.\n\n10. What: add scenario fixtures.\nWhy: required by FR-12 and FR-13.\nHow: add `tests/gha-agent/clean/scenario.env` and issue fixture with minimal valid/invalid workflow files under `.github/workflows`.\nEdge cases: make issue file deterministic (invalid runs-on/type, expression syntax, etc.) and avoid ambiguous YAML warnings.\nTests: run scenario label checks via `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent`.\nRisks: too-brittle fixture depending on specific actionlint version/version-specific warnings.\n\n11. What: update distribution docs.\nWhy: FR-13 requires installer and docs updates to make agent visible and installable.\nHow: modify `install.sh` `SKILLS`, dependency hints, and AGENTS snippet for gha-agent; update README available-agent row and quick usage section.\nEdge cases: keep existing installation order and interactive prompts intact.\nTests: validate installer help snippet includes gha-agent line and `run all` discoverability not harmed.\nRisks: accidental format regression in install dependency checks.\n\n12. What: run validation and complete sign-off.\nWhy: confirm acceptance criteria and catch integration/regression issues before WORK phase.\nHow: run `tests/run-scenarios.sh gha-agent`, shellcheck on new script+SKILL and relevant files via `tests/run-scenarios.sh shellcheck`, then `ralph validate work`.\nEdge cases: fixture/tool mismatch should be explicit skips vs fails.\nTests: full plan-phase checks.\nRisks: validation toolchain dependency (shellcheck missing) causing false failure.\n\n13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n\n## Decision Log\n\n- Decision 1: Use per-spec shared-lib source pattern instead of local utility duplication.\n  - Options considered: keep duplicated bootstrap code in new script, or source `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\n  - Chosen: source shared lib.\n  - Why: consistent with backlog scope and line budget.\n  - Impact: lower maintenance, same patterns as existing agents, uniform fail-safe semantics.\n\n- Decision 2: Implement strict skip-first behavior for missing `.github/workflows`.\n  - Options considered: return FAIL, return SKIP, auto-create dir.\n  - Chosen: `SKIP` with explicit reason.\n  - Why: aligns FR-4 requirement text and avoids false failures in non-GHA repos.\n  - Impact: predictable behavior for repos with only Terraform/Python etc.\n\n- Decision 3: Preserve local command semantics for `all` with one-step body.\n  - Options considered: special-case `all` with no step expansion vs route through `lint`.\n  - Chosen: route `all` through step dispatch to keep consistent `overall_ok` and fail-fast handling.\n  - Why: future-proofing for additional steps.\n  - Impact: minimal complexity and consistent UX across agents.\n\n## Edge Cases and Risks\n\n- `.github/workflows` directory does not exist in repo.\n- CHANGED_FILES set but no workflow path matches and no direct discovery files exist.\n- CHANGED_FILES contains non-workflow files only.\n- CHANGED_FILES path separators differ on platform (existing convention keeps space-delimited paths only).\n- `actionlint` unavailable even though fixture says required tool present.\n- actionlint emits non-zero while no output, or output without diagnostics.\n- Help invoked before toolchain install or from non-repo directory.\n- CI versus local behavior around log line truncation due shared MAX_LINES defaults.\n- Installer path mismatch on remote install if `gha-agent` files absent or script not executable.\n- README/AGENTS snippets can become stale if not updated with new agent line.\n","numLines":309,"startLine":1,"totalLines":309}}}
